## PART B — Unlearn: prune every stale or wrong rule

A rule that no longer reflects reality is worse than no rule — it
costs the agent attention on every turn AND points at a bad pattern.
Be just as eager to remove or rewrite rules as you are to add them.

### When this fires

After ANY of the following, you MUST revise or delete the offending
rule(s) in the same task:

- A rule's recipe is now obsolete (framework upgrade, library API
  change, deprecated primitive).
- A rule contradicts a newer, better rule you've just written.
- A rule was based on an incorrect assumption that you've since
  disproved.
- A rule keeps being misapplied because it's too vague or too broad.
- A rule has not prevented a single real bug in the period it has
  been active, AND it generates friction (false positives, churn,
  noisy lints).
- A rule is duplicated by another rule. Pick the better one and
  delete the rest.
- A rule's stack-specific recipe is irrelevant to this project (e.g.
  you copied the rulebook to a non-Flutter project — delete
  `flutter-*.mdc` recipes).

### What "unlearning" means

Pick the smallest correct action — in priority order:

1. **Narrow the rule.** Tighten the wording, add an "Applies when"
   clause, restrict the `globs:` frontmatter so it stops firing in
   the wrong contexts.
2. **Rewrite the rule.** Replace the bad recipe with the correct one
   and add a one-line "Why we changed this" note inside the rule
   body so future readers know it was deliberate.
3. **Supersede the rule.** Create the replacement rule, then delete
   the old one in the same commit. Don't leave the stale rule lying
   around marked "deprecated" — agents will still read it.
4. **Delete the rule outright.** If the rule no longer serves the
   project, just remove the file. Note the deletion in your task
   summary.

### What an unlearn entry must contain

When you remove or rewrite a rule, the task summary MUST include:

- **What rule(s) you changed or deleted** (file paths).
- **Why it was wrong / stale** (one sentence — what we used to
  believe, what we now know).
- **What replaces it** (link to the new rule, or "no replacement
  needed because…").

### Example (unlearn)

> **Removed:** `.cursor/rules/old-modal-pattern.mdc`.
> **Why stale:** advised wrapping every sheet body in `Padding +
> Column(min) + Flexible`. We learned this overflows by drag-handle
> + safe-area on short screens.
> **Replacement:** the `LayoutBuilder + Column(max) + Expanded`
> recipe in `flutter-overflow-safety.mdc`.

